The study of the sources of the text of the pro Cluentio reveals problems of great difficulty. With the exception of a fragmentary palimpsest (P), there is really no manu- script of first-class authority : those 011 which recent editors have mainly relied (s and ⁷1¹) are not considered of any account for the text of the other speeches which they contain, and the version of the pro Cluentio which they present derives support more from inference and analogy than from the intrinsic authority of the codices them— selves. It was Classen who first remodelled the text on the basis of these two manuscripts. Till his edition appeared, in 1831, editors had been content to follow the vulgate pretty much in the form in which it exists in the numerous Mss. of Cicero that are scattered among the libraries of Europe. These are mostly Italian Mss. of the fifteenth and even the sixteenth century, belonging to the class of which Baiter has tersely said “interpolatis codiczbus Italici-s nulla fides haberi potest.''
